          "buttonOnMobile": false,
          "label": "<p>A neuron in the dorsal root ganglion has a single T-shaped process that divides </p>",
          "x": 30,
          "y": 30,
          "width": 40,
          "height": 25,
          "libraryTitle": "Multiple Choice",
          "action": {
            "library": "H5P.MultiChoice 1.16",
            "params": {
              "question": "<p>A neuron in the dorsal root ganglion has a single T-shaped process that divides into a peripheral and a central branch. How is this neuron classified by structure and function?</p>",
              "answers": [
                {
                  "text": "<div>Bipolar neuron; motor function</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Bipolar neurons have one dendrite and one axon as separate processes. Dorsal root ganglion neurons are sensory, not motor.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>Multipolar neuron; sensory function</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Multipolar neurons have many dendrites and one axon. The single T-shaped process is the hallmark of pseudounipolar neurons, not multipolar.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>Pseudounipolar neuron; sensory function</div>",
                  "correct": true,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Correct. Dorsal root ganglion neurons are pseudounipolar with a single process that splits in a T-shape into peripheral and central branches. They serve as primary sensory neurons.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>Unipolar neuron; interneuron function</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>True unipolar neurons are rare in humans. The T-shaped bifurcating process makes these pseudounipolar, and they are sensory neurons, not interneurons.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                }
              ],
              "overallFeedback": [
                {
                  "from": 0,
                  "to": 50,
                  "feedback": "Dorsal root ganglion neurons are pseudounipolar — they have a single process that divides into a T-shaped peripheral and central branch. They are primary sensory neurons, not motor or interneurons."
                },
                {
                  "from": 51,
                  "to": 100,
                  "feedback": "Excellent. Pseudounipolar neurons in the dorsal root ganglion are the primary sensory neurons of the body, carrying afferent information to the spinal cord via their central branch."
                }
              ],
